item.title: Iran Ships Fuel to Venezuela, Flouting U.S. Pressure
item.description: The first of five tankers carrying Iranian fuel has reached gasoline-starved Venezuela in a show of defiance by two U.S. adversaries flouting American sanctions aimed at unseating their authoritarian governments.

item.title: More Than 100 in Germany Found to Be Infected With Coronavirus After Church's Services
item.description: At least 107 people have been found to be infected with the new coronavirus after some of them attended Sunday services at a church in Frankfurt two weeks ago, according to German officials, highlighting the growing risk of new outbreaks of the virus as Germany loosens restrictions on public gatherings.

item.title: Protests Reignite in Hong Kong Over Beijing's Security Measure
item.description: Tear gas returned to the streets of Hong Kong as riot police converged on protesters who defied social-distancing rules to vent anger at Beijing’s move to swiftly impose national-security law.

item.title: Netanyahu's Trial Begins, Kicking Off Lengthy Legal Fight
item.description: Benjamin Netanyahu appeared in a Jerusalem courtroom to hear charges of bribery and breach of trust leveled against him—the first time a sitting Israeli prime minister has been put on trial.

item.title: Deprived of the Rites of Grief, Italians Search for Ways to Remember Covid-19 Victims
item.description: Families struggle to fill the void as coronavirus lockdowns ease, hampered by funeral fees and, for some, a search for ashes

item.title: Iraq Turns to Neighbors to Ease Economic Strains
item.description: Under pressure from low oil prices, Iraq is seeking debt relief from Kuwait and moving to bolster commercial links with Saudi Arabia.
